                        <hr>
                        <p>For Nic Pottebaum, receiving a Hancher-Finkbine Medallion, one of Iowa’s more prestigious awards, is not only an honor but instills pride in being a student at the UI. As a recent graduate and the former UISG president for the 2012-2013 academic year, his work as a campus leader was not something easily acquired, but required hard work and real world experience.</p>
                        <p>“Somewhere along the way I became a campus leader, but I never thought of it as striving for that title,” says Pottebaum. “Rather, I saw the opportunities that made me a campus leader just an opportunity to benefit my fellow students.”</p>
                        <p>The recent Iowa graduate was one of seven on campus who earned an award for their work on campus. This annual tradition of recognizing campus leaders had earnest beginnings as simply an event to bring people together on campus. Starting in 1917, dinners sponsored by William Finkbine and Carl Kuhnle were meant to gather leaders on campus, both students and professionals, to create connections and lasting ties on campus. The dinners were proven to be so successful that Finkbine created an endowment for them to continue.</p>
                        <p>Each year a total of seven students, faculty, staff, and alumni are invited to attend the Finkbine dinner along with the UI president, deans, and other members of the UI. It is Finkbine’s hope that the leaders of the UI would come together to have a better understanding of each other and their shared concern for the livelihood of the university. Four students, one professor, one staff member, and one alumnus are given awards for their outstanding work on campus.</p>
                        <p>“Every time I just get amazed [by the students] because they do something different that I have just never heard of before,” says Belinda Marner, Assistant Vice President for Student Life and Chair of the Finkbine Dinner Committee. “It’s one of the highlights of the year for me because you just think about all the things these people are doing and where they’re going - it’s amazing to think about.”</p>
                        <p>The purpose of honoring attendees with medallions is to recognize leadership, learning, and loyalty. The tradition of awarding medallions was established in 1964. These medallions are named after William Finkbine as well as Virgil Hancher who was a guest at the first dinner and served as president of the UI for 24 years.</p>
                        <p>Pottebaum believes these positive qualities are important to honor at the university. Every student no matter who they are and how they serve on campus should attain these qualities and use them whether they be on another college campus or in another part of the world.</p>
                        <p>“My experience at Iowa taught me to balance many things while always valuing those around and doing things the right way,” says Pottebaum. “There are countless failures and successes I learned in my four years that will guide me for the rest of my life.”</p>
                    </div>
