                <h2 class="text-center">Awarding Commitment</h2>
                <h4 class="text-center">Hawkeye Leadership &amp; Service Awards honor students for their commitment to campus and community.</h4>
                <hr>
                <div class="colgroup">
                    <div class="col-1-2">
                        <p>Attending college is not only about excelling academically, but also using those skills outside of the classroom. For Sydney Mason, a member of Walk It Out, attending college means working with local businesses to celebrate diversity, fashion, and raise awareness for HIV/AIDS-related issues. Walk It Out (WIO) is one of several student organizations recognized at the Hawkeye Leadership & Service Awards held on May 1st at the Iowa Memorial Union.</p>
                        <p>“It’s an amazing feeling to be recognized for the hard work we do throughout the year,” says Mason, a UI senior in Anthropology and Geography.
                        The Hawkeye Leadership & Service Awards celebrated the accomplishments of student organizations, student leaders, student organization advisors, and campus partners. The Center for Student Involvement and Leadership (CSIL) works hard each year to find new ways to honor all of the unique contributions students make to both local and global causes.</p>
                        <p>"I think that there are a lot of cool things that our students are doing,” says Paul Mintner, Coordinator for Leadership Programs in CSIL. “The commitment that students have for their student organizations and the work that they do is a great developmental thing."</p>
                        <p>Although the strength of the academic programs at UI is at the core of what attracts students to the university, academics are not everything, according to Mintner. By being part of student organizations, students can implement many of the skills they learn in the classroom in a co-curricular setting that benefits the campus and the community. Membership in a student organization also allows students to explore different interests while putting academic skills to use.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-1-2">
                        <p>“I think it’s good to have students actively engaged in what they care about,” says Mintner. “I think that says a lot about the type of student that comes to Iowa and the students that we want to have here.”</p>
                        <p>There are many different corners of the university that students can explore through student organizations. Mason was drawn to Walk It Out in 2009 because of her interest in diversity and promoting HIV/AIDS awareness. This year, Walk It Out is one of two student organizations that won an award for their Outstanding Diversity Awareness Program.</p>
                        <p>“Along with promoting HIV/AIDS awareness, WIO also encourages students and community members of any ethnicity and orientation to become involved in our events,” says Mason. “We believe this allows for people to not only expand their horizons and learn about the various cultures in the area, but also be proud of their heritage and showcase their cultural roots in a positive environment.”
                        Walk It Out’s engagement exemplifies what the Hawkeye Leadership & Service Awards are about. According to Mintner, the efforts of these students are a reflection of what the University of Iowa strives to do for local and global communities.</p>
                        <p>“The [Hawkeye Awards] are meant to honor the undergraduate and the graduate student experience,” says Mintner. “I think that’s a special thing about it, too, is that it’s meant to honor any student who attends this institution and  [has] a strong commitment to be involved and make a contribution than just attending this university.”</p>
                        <p>For a full list of award recipients, follow this link: Hawkeye Awards 2012-2013 – Winners List.</p>
